\b Data compression\b0  deals with the way the space needed to represent a certain quantity of information can be reduced. It intervenes in both data transmission and data storage. \par
\par
First, you have to know that sound is a wave. The frequency of sound is often expressed in Hertz (Hz.) Frequency is directly linked to the perceived pitch\b  \b0 of a sound, but it is not the only parameter characterizing it. Very low frequencies correspond to low pitches and very high frequencies correspond to high pitches.\par
\par
The sound emitted by a vibrating tuning fork is (almost) pure. It can be represented by a simple smooth sine function.\par
\par
A sine function requires very little storage place. Thus, to record the sound emitted by a vibrating tuning fork, only the corresponding sine function is required.\par
\par
If a harmonic sound (dotted curve) is added to this simple sound (also dotted), both superimpose to form the global sound represented by the curve below (in bold).\par
\par
The combined wave is more complex then the vibrating tuning fork's wave, but since it can be expressed as the sum of two sine functions, one simply needs to store both these functions into the database.\par
\par
A tuning fork is an instrument that gives a fixed sound used as a reference to the note of A placed in the second space of the treble clef staff. Its frequency is 440 Hz (440 vibrations per second). This sound can be heard when a French telephone is picked up.\par
\par
However, most sound we hear when listenning to music are a lot more complex.\par
\par
This is where Fourier transforms come into play. A Fourier transform is a mathematical operation that turns a given wave into a simple sum of sine and cosine functions. To record a sound, these sine and cosine functions are simply stored into a database.\par
\par
Moreover, living beings can only perceive a limited range of the sound spectrum. According to physiologists, the average human ear only perceives sounds within a range of 20 Hz (under this frequency, sound waves are called infrasounds.) to 20 kHz (over this frequency, sound waves are called ultrasounds.). This range varies slightly with age, culture, etc. If the intensity of a sound is too low, the human ear will not perceive it. If it is too high, the sound will very likely cause ear damage. Here is a plot illustrating this reality.  \par
\par
This brings us back to data compression. When compressing a sound wave, the sine and cosine functions that are not perceptible to the human ear can safely be ignored. A large amount of space can be saved nd the human ear will hear no difference. This would not be the case for the ear of other animal species. For example, bats and dolphins can perceive sounds of frquencies up to 100 kHz. Thus, as opposed to a human being, when a dolphin listens to MP3 compressed music, it does not quite hear the same as the original version. Here is a plot representing the frequency (in Hertz) of the sound emitted by a bat with respect to time. \par
